"# Appendix A — A Tiny Proof Assistant in Scheme

Where we push the natural-deduction checker of chapter 3 one step
further into an *interactive* system with tactics — the shape of Coq
or Isabelle, in one hundred lines.

Chapter 3 built a proof *checker* that verifies purported proofs. This
appendix builds a proof *assistant*: an interactive session where the
user has a *goal* to prove and applies *tactics* that reduce the goal
to sub-goals until every sub-goal is trivially discharged.

The core data structure is the *goal state*: a list of remaining
subgoals, each with its own context of assumptions. A tactic
transforms one goal state into another (possibly empty) goal state.
When the state becomes empty, the proof is complete.

## Goal states

```scheme
;; A subgoal: (ctx . conclusion)
;;   ctx: list of assumption formulas
;;   conclusion: formula to prove
;;
;; A goal state: list of subgoals.

(define (make-goal ctx conclusion) (cons ctx conclusion))
(define (goal-ctx  g) (car g))
(define (goal-concl g) (cdr g))

(define initial-state (lambda (concl) (list (make-goal '() concl))))
```

The initial state, given a formula to prove, is a single subgoal with
that formula and no assumptions.

## Tactics

A *tactic* is a function that transforms the goal state. Some tactics
succeed and produce a new state; others fail. Failing gracefully is
important — the user should be able to try a tactic and back out if it
does not work.

The core tactics we need mirror the natural-deduction rules from
chapter 3.

- **`intro`.** For a goal of the form `(implies P Q)`, add P to the
  context and change the goal to Q. Corresponds to `impl-intro`.
- **`split`.** For a goal of the form `(and P Q)`, produce two subgoals:
  P and Q, each in the same context. Corresponds to `conj-intro`.
- **`left`, `right`.** For a goal of the form `(or P Q)`, pick which
  side to prove. Corresponds to `disj-intro-l` or `disj-intro-r`.
- **`assumption`.** If the current goal is one of the assumptions in
  the context, discharge it.
- **`apply`.** For a goal Q and an assumption `(implies P Q)` (matched
  against something in context), produce the subgoal P.
- **`destruct`.** For an assumption of form `(and P Q)`, replace it
  with two assumptions P and Q. Or for `(or P Q)`, split the current
  subgoal into two — one where the assumption is P, one where it is Q.

Each tactic works on the *first* subgoal in the state (the *focused*
subgoal).

```scheme
(define (tactic-intro state)
  (let* ((g       (car state))
         (rest    (cdr state))
         (concl   (goal-concl g)))
    (if (and (pair? concl) (eq? (car concl) 'implies))
        (cons (make-goal (cons (cadr concl) (goal-ctx g))
                          (caddr concl))
              rest)
        (error \"intro: goal is not an implication\" concl))))

(define (tactic-split state)
  (let* ((g       (car state))
         (rest    (cdr state))
         (concl   (goal-concl g)))
    (if (and (pair? concl) (eq? (car concl) 'and))
        (cons (make-goal (goal-ctx g) (cadr concl))
              (cons (make-goal (goal-ctx g) (caddr concl))
                    rest))
        (error \"split: goal is not a conjunction\" concl))))

(define (tactic-left state)
  (let* ((g (car state)) (rest (cdr state)) (concl (goal-concl g)))
    (if (and (pair? concl) (eq? (car concl) 'or))
        (cons (make-goal (goal-ctx g) (cadr concl)) rest)
        (error \"left: goal is not a disjunction\" concl))))

(define (tactic-right state)
  (let* ((g (car state)) (rest (cdr state)) (concl (goal-concl g)))
    (if (and (pair? concl) (eq? (car concl) 'or))
        (cons (make-goal (goal-ctx g) (caddr concl)) rest)
        (error \"right: goal is not a disjunction\" concl))))

(define (tactic-assumption state)
  (let* ((g (car state)) (rest (cdr state)) (concl (goal-concl g)))
    (if (member concl (goal-ctx g))
        rest                    ; drop this subgoal; it is discharged
        (error \"assumption: not in context\" concl))))

(define (tactic-apply hyp state)
  ;; hyp is an implication (implies P concl) in the context;
  ;; reduce the current goal to proving P.
  (let* ((g (car state)) (rest (cdr state)) (concl (goal-concl g)))
    (cond
      ((not (member hyp (goal-ctx g)))
       (error \"apply: hypothesis not in context\" hyp))
      ((not (and (pair? hyp) (eq? (car hyp) 'implies)
                 (equal? (caddr hyp) concl)))
       (error \"apply: hypothesis does not conclude with goal\" hyp))
      (else
       (cons (make-goal (goal-ctx g) (cadr hyp)) rest)))))
```

Six tactics; each is a small transformation. That is essentially the
entire theorem-proving apparatus at the propositional level.

## A worked interaction

Prove `(implies P (implies Q P))`. This is a small classical theorem
(constant function returns first argument).

```scheme
(define state1 (initial-state '(implies P (implies Q P))))
;; state1: [ (() . (implies P (implies Q P))) ]

(define state2 (tactic-intro state1))
;; state2: [ ((P) . (implies Q P)) ]

(define state3 (tactic-intro state2))
;; state3: [ ((Q P) . P) ]

(define state4 (tactic-assumption state3))
;; state4: [ ]
;; Empty! Proof complete.
```

Four tactics, one theorem. The Scheme session captures the
back-and-forth of an interactive proof.

## Composition of tactics

Real proof assistants (Coq, Lean, Isabelle) have *tactic combinators*
that compose tactics into strategies:

- `seq t1 t2` — first apply t1, then t2 to the result.
- `orelse t1 t2` — try t1; if it fails, try t2.
- `repeat t` — apply t repeatedly until it fails.
- `all t` — apply t to every subgoal.

```scheme
(define (tac-seq t1 t2)
  (lambda (state)
    (t2 (t1 state))))

(define (tac-orelse t1 t2)
  (lambda (state)
    (with-exception-handler
      (lambda (exn) (t2 state))
      (lambda () (t1 state)))))

(define (tac-repeat t)
  (lambda (state)
    ((tac-orelse (tac-seq t (tac-repeat t))
                 (lambda (s) s))
     state)))
```

With these combinators you can express high-level strategies:

    (tac-repeat (tac-orelse tactic-intro
                             (tac-orelse tactic-split
                                          tactic-assumption)))

This *auto* tactic will try `intro`, then `split`, then `assumption`,
repeatedly, until no more progress is possible. For small propositional
theorems, it often finds a proof unaided.

## Extending to predicate logic

For quantifiers we need two more tactics:

- **`intro-forall`.** For a goal `(forall ?x phi)`, introduce a fresh
  variable c not appearing in the context, and change the goal to
  `phi[?x := c]`.
- **`instantiate`.** For an assumption `(forall ?x phi)`, add
  `phi[?x := t]` to the context for a specific term t.

The freshness condition on `intro-forall` requires tracking which
variables are used; the appendix keeps this bookkeeping straightforward.

## Tactic-generated proof terms

An assistant is *complete* only if it produces a *proof term* — a
value in the Curry-Howard sense that certifies the theorem. We can
extend the tactic language so every tactic step also builds a term.

```scheme
;; Extended state: (subgoals . proof-so-far)
;; proof-so-far is a partial proof term with holes for each subgoal.

;; When tactic-intro fires on goal (implies P Q):
;;   the corresponding proof term is (lambda (x) hole),
;;   where x binds the assumption and hole will be filled by the sub-proof of Q.

;; When tactic-assumption discharges a hole with variable x:
;;   the hole becomes x.

;; When the state is empty, the proof-so-far is a complete proof term.
```

Building the proof term alongside the tactic reduction is what
distinguishes a *proof assistant* from a mere *proof searcher*. The
term is *the proof* — it is what you export, publish, or feed to an
extraction tool.

## Comparison to Coq

Coq is a full proof assistant with:

- Dependent types (a much richer type theory than STLC).
- Hundreds of built-in tactics.
- User-programmable tactics (Ltac, Ltac2, Mtac).
- A large standard library.
- An extraction machinery to OCaml, Haskell, Scheme.

Our tiny assistant has none of these. But the pattern is the same:
goal state, tactics, tactic combinators, proof terms. The scale differs;
the shape is identical.

## What to try

Extend with `destruct` and `case-analysis` tactics. These are the ones
that pattern-match on conjunctions and disjunctions in the context.

Add a `contradiction` tactic: if the context contains both P and (not P),
any goal is discharged. This is the *ex falso* rule.

Implement a small *decision procedure* for pure propositional logic:
given a goal, check whether it is a tautology by truth-table (chapter
1) and, if so, construct the corresponding proof term automatically.
This is the *tauto* tactic in Coq.

## Closing

A proof assistant is a UI over a proof checker. Add goal state, add
tactics, add combinators — you have the essential shape. Scale it up
with more tactics, better search, richer types, and you have Coq.
Scale it in a different direction with a graphical interface and
students, and you have a teaching tool.

The core insight of this appendix: proof assistance is a
transformation on goal states, and every tactic is a small program.
Building one at this scale strips away the mystique. The tactic
`intro` really is one line of code.
"
